<Base active="faq" title="FAQ — Nightcone Labs" description="Frequently asked questions about Nightcone Labs: oneirogens, the 14-night protocol, how experiments are scored, safety, and the public matrix.">

  <div class="hero" style="padding:72px 0 48px">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h1>Questions, answered plainly.</h1>
      <p class="lede" style="max-width:54ch">What Nightcone is, how the experiments run, and where the limits are.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section style="padding-top:24px">
    <div class="wrap" style="max-width:760px">

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is an oneirogen?</h3>
        <p>An oneirogen is a substance reported to produce or enhance dream states — sharper recall, more vivid or bizarre imagery, sometimes lucidity. The category is broad and mostly traditional: ethnobotanical dream herbs, a few vitamins and amino acids, and the cholinergic compounds borrowed from the lucid-dreaming community. "Reported" is the operative word. Most of these claims have never been tested under controlled conditions.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What does Nightcone actually do?</h3>
        <p>It runs single-variable self-experiments on these compounds and publishes the results as a growing matrix. One compound, one fixed protocol, run long enough to see past night-to-night noise. Each experiment is written up as a short video and logged as a row of data: substance, dose, protocol, recall score, lucidity score, notes.</p>
        <p>It is a research log presented in public, not a store and not a wellness program. There is nothing for sale.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why fourteen nights?</h3>
        <p>Because dreams are noisy. Any single night can be vivid or blank for reasons that have nothing to do with what you took. Fourteen consecutive nights at a fixed dose and fixed timing — with a washout period when it's relevant — gives enough of a baseline to tell an acute effect from a build-up effect, and either from random variation. Shorter trials are mostly storytelling.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why test one compound at a time?</h3>
        <p>Because stacking destroys attribution. Traditional dream preparations are usually blends — ubulawu froth medicines might contain three or more plants. If a blend produces an effect, you can't say which ingredient did it. Isolating the variable is slower and less exciting, and it's the only way to learn anything reliable. No stacking, no behavioural techniques layered in, no journaling unless journaling is the thing being tested.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How are recall and lucidity scored?</h3>
        <p>On a 0–5 scale, subjectively, against the experimenter's own baseline. These are single-subject ratings, not instrumented measurements — there's no polysomnography, no blinding, no second observer. We say so plainly. The scores are useful as a consistent internal yardstick across experiments, not as clinical data.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Has anything actually worked?</h3>
        <p>A few things, modestly. Galantamine produced the clearest lucidity signal — three lucid dreams in fourteen nights. Vitamin B6 reliably increased recall (and it's the one compound here with a real controlled trial behind it). Calea zacatechichi pushed vividness and bizarreness. Most other compounds did less than their reputations suggest, and several did nothing measurable. That's the honest distribution.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why publish the failures?</h3>
        <p>Because a documented non-effect is genuinely useful — it saves the next person two weeks. Most things, tested honestly, don't do much. A project that only published its hits would be a marketing channel, not a research log. Null and ambiguous findings get the same treatment as the wins.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you explain how these compounds work?</h3>
        <p>Only as far as the evidence allows. For some — the cholinergic compounds and their effect on REM, for example — there's a plausible, well-characterised mechanism, and we'll name it while flagging that the dream-specific link is unproven. For most oneirogens the mechanism is poorly studied or unknown, and we say that rather than inventing a pathway. Hypothesis-level stays labelled as hypothesis-level.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is this medical or scientific advice?</h3>
        <p>No. Nightcone documents one person's self-experimentation for research interest. It is not medical advice, not a recommendation to take anything, and not peer-reviewed science. Several compounds discussed carry real toxicity and drug-interaction risks — some dream herbs are genuinely dangerous at the doses folklore suggests. Do your own research and talk to a clinician before ingesting anything.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How do you handle the cultural traditions?</h3>
        <p>With context and respect. Many of these plants come from living divination and healing traditions — the Southern Bantu ubulawu practice, Egyptian dream-temple history, and others. We reference the ethnography and the academic sources, use the correct terms, and avoid repackaging sacred practice as wellness mysticism. When we isolate a plant from a traditional blend, we say what we're removing and why.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Where can I follow the work?</h3>
        <p>The running record lives on the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/@nightcone_labs" target="_blank" rel="noopener">@nightcone_labs YouTube</a> and <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@nightcone_labs" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TikTok</a> channels — each clip is one matrix entry. For anything else, reach the lab via the <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
